            "<p>This version of Modern Philosophy is a derivative copy of Modern Philosophy created by <a href=\"http:\/\/baruffio.com\/modernphilosophy\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Alex Dunn<\/a>, who based his work on the original Modern Philosophy book create by <a href=\"https:\/\/filebox.vt.edu\/users\/ottw\/modtext.html\">Walter Ott.<\/a><\/p><p>This version of Modern Philosophy is released under a <a href=\"http:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creative Commons Attribution NonCommercial ShareAlike 3.0 Unported license<\/a>. The only modifications made to this version from both the original and the modification done by Alex Dunn the original is the format has been changed. No content has been modified.<\/p><p>The original version of Modern Philosophy was created from public domain resources by\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/filebox.vt.edu\/users\/ottw\/modtext.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Walter Ott<\/a> with contributors from Antonia LoLordo and Lydia Patton. Contributions not in the public domain and created by Walter, Antonia or Lydia for the original were released under a Creative Commons <a href=\"http:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License<\/a>. Alex Dunn&#8217;s derivative version was also released under a Creative Commons <a href=\"http:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License<\/a><\/p>",
        "pb_about_50":
            "This is a textbook (or better, a workbook) in modern philosophy. It combines readings from primary sources with two pedagogical tools. Paragraphs in italics introduce figures and texts. Numbered study questions (also in italics) ask students to reconstruct an argument or position from the text, or draw connections among the readings. The introductory chapter, Minilogic and Glossary, are designed to present the basic tools of philosophy and sketch some principles and positions.",
        "pb_about_unlimited":
            "<p>This version of the Modern Philosophy textbook was created on August 28, 2013 as part of the <a href=\"http:\/\/open.bccampus.ca\">BC Open Textbook<\/a> project.<\/p><p><strong>Description from original book author Walter Ott<\/strong><\/p><p>This is a textbook (or better, a workbook) in modern philosophy. It combines readings from primary sources with two pedagogical tools. Paragraphs in italics introduce figures and texts. Numbered study questions (also in italics) ask students to reconstruct an argument or position from the text, or draw connections among the readings. And I have added an introductory chapter (Chapter 0 \u2013 Minilogic and Glossary), designed to present the basic tools of philosophy and sketch some principles and positions.<\/p><p>The immediate goal is to encourage students to grapple with the ideas rather than passing their eyes over the texts. This makes for a better classroom experience and permits higher-level discussions.<\/p><p>Another goal is to encourage collaboration among instructors, as they revise and post their own versions of the book.<\/p><p>You&#8217;re invited to use the book in your courses.<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p>",
